# Rationale and Reflection

## Design and Development Process

Multiple colour palettes were created during the assignment. From left to right, the first palette was a conceptual colour palette that was put together early in the design process. The second palette was a colour palette used early in the development process, using darker browns. The third palette is a colour palette used later in the development process, using lighter greens in place of browns, bringing lighter tones into the website.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In the early stages of design, many elements of the website were inspired by the Bootstrap Framework. I wanted to have a website where each element of a webpage flowed easily from one to another, using minimalistic icons and font, drawing focus more to the content as opposed to the look, as having too many styalized elements such as unique and bold font would be too much of a visual eyesore and may even be hard to read. Due to time constraints, a website that truly looked like it was built using the Bootstrap Framework was not possible, and I wanted to adhere to the layout of the website set in the design stage. In the end, I stuck with a more simple, geometric, and ordered look for the website, focusing and highlighting the content in the website, as that is what visitors for the website would be interested in seeing.

## Challenges Faced and Solutions

One of the main challenges faced during this assignment was properly formatting images throughout the website. Often, the problem was that the CSS container the images were in weren&#39;t quite big enough to show all the details that needed to be shown, running the risk of leaving details out that may be necessary to highlight a certain point. The main issue for this was because I wanted to keep the website in-line with the established wireframe and initial designs. Eventually I decided that for some images that really needed changing, their containers would be adjusted to both show the details that needed to be shown, as well as keep to the original conceptual designs. The proper formatting of images was also an issue coding-wise, mainly with the logo images in the header and footer. Often, they would not be formatted correctly where text next to the image would warp around the image, or the image wouldn&#39;t properly fit into the navigation bar. This was resolved by using multiple CSS classes and a lot of trial and error until it was formatted how I wanted it and at a presentable standard.

Another main challenge faced during this assignment was making the website properly responsive so that it would look presentable across a variety of devices, mainly phones, tablets, and desktops. Initially I believed that this would be a major issue as I had done the website and its formatting for desktop devices first, more specifically for devices with a screen width of 1920 pixels. This was before I realized that it was recommended that the website be designed for mobile devices first, then build up from there. However, due to the existing formatting and layout of the website, mainly the navigation bar, building the website to be responsive and usable for mobile devices was not as big of an issue as I initially believed. To help with making the website responsive, I used media queries to make the necessary changes if the device&#39;s width was less than a determined amount. For the breakpoints, I made the mobile devices size a maximum of 600 pixels wide, the tablet size was a maximum of 800 pixels wide, and the laptop and desktop sizes were larger than 800 pixels wide. I chose these sizes because I based the breakpoints roughly off the Developer Tool responsive screen widths in the web browser application Brave, as it was the only program I had access to that I could test my website responsiveness with.
